https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P8JoEI8IPsY']]), ('Pockets holdin’ hope', [["“Pockets holdin' hope” literally is saying that the only thing that Cole had to his name at that time was hope, only a dream of what one day he could/wanted to be. Interesting is that he says that it’s his pockets that are “holding” hope, which means that his life at that point was so low that even his very pockets had to grab on and barely was holding on to the little hope he had at the time.

A similiar line was also said by JAY-Z back in 2001 on his song Renegade,
“Feelin' braver, durag wrappin' my waves up, pockets full of hope”

in the same way Cole reflects on his tough past and upbringing, that one day would fill his pockets with much more than just hope."]]), ('Where my young niggas choppin’ up grams
 And them choppers won’t pry from they hands
 Packin’ lead like they got a exam', [['Throughout this song, Cole raps about his teenage years. Here, he talks about some of his friends that became involved in the gangster lifestyle, where they were “choppin’ up grams” (managing drugs) and wielding “choppers” (guns).

Cole creates a double entendre when discussing his friends “packin’ lead.” It literally refers to the lead ammunition for their guns, but Cole ties this to the mention of an “exam” because the graphite within pencils is often (and wrongly) referred to as “lead.” Of course, pencils are the required utensil for most examinations.']]), ('Deep down inside, though, I still feel as broke
 As that nigga who just graduated from college', [['J. Cole graduated from St. John’s University in Queens, New York in 2007, earning magna cum laude honors and accruing a 3.82 GPA over his tenure. He detailed his college lifestyle in his May 2007 track, “College Boy,” which was released right as he was graduating from school.

Cole spoke about his financial situation post-graduation in an interview with Interview Magazine in February of 2013:

Ah, man. Well, actually, I graduated magna cum laude. And after college, man, that was… Well, I was broke as hell. I was renting an apartment in Queens with my roommates during school, and after we graduated, they moved out and started their careers. I didn’t really have a career at that point[…] Well, I was hitting my mom up for money. I kept hitting other people up for money, too. I just felt like a bum. I owed thousands of dollars in rent and I was just waiting on my deal. My landlord was always letting me slide, but eventually I had to give him something, even just to show that I had income. So my homie hooked me up with this job at a newspaper.

Cole hasn’t forgotten that part of his life, however. He remains close with his aforementioned landlord, Mohammad, and even paid him back his missed rent and some once he got his deal.']]), ('Sound like a whole Lambo’ truck in my stomach
 Bitch, I ain’t hungry, this feeling is starving', [['Cole reflects on his past when he was broke and couldn’t afford to eat. He was hungry to the point his stomach rumbled so loud that it sounded like a Lambo truck. The car in question is the Lamborghini Urus, Lamborghini being a luxury sports car manufacturer known for it’s fast and deafening loud cars.

“LamboTruck” was also a song on J. Cole’s label, Dreamville’s, 2019 album Revenge of the Dreamers III. In the song, Dreamville Records signee Cozz goes on to say that Cole actually drives a Lamborghini Urus:

Cole just pulled up in a Lamborghini truck

J. Cole continues this verse by speaking on how he needs to stay dedicated to finally make it. Therefore, the double-meaning of these bars is that Cole was not only hungry for success, but starving for it, and kept working until he finally got the Lambo truck that may have been foreshadowed in his past. Coincidentally, a theme throughout “LamboTruck” is being hungry as a young artist, which can be seen in Cozz’s lyrics:

I just ate, but still I’m hungry

and

Nigga, this hunger got me finna choke




The Laborghini Urus in the “LamboTruck” music video']]), ('Niggas wanted me to look the part, had to stop takin’ advice
 Put the jewelry to the side, had to find me, had to find God', [['At the current stage of his career, Cole is known for his modesty and reserved persona. Some even say that Cole dresses like he’s homeless, something that Dreamville signee JID played off of in a skit on his November 2018 song, “Workin Out”:

Why that nigga J. Cole got all this money [but] look like he ‘bout to borrow somebody charger or something?

However, when Cole was still a rising artist, he often chose to dress like “the traditional rapper,” wearing expensive jewelry and clothing.



The most notable instance of this was Cole’s outfit at the 2013 BET Awards, pictured above. After two other artists wore the exact same thing, it became a public spectacle of “Who Wore It Best?”

Cole recalled this in his March 2019 GQ interview. He said that he wanted to wear something else, but the people around him were trying to convince him that the Versace sweater and chain were the things that would make him be perceived as a superstar, which is what he was longing for at the time.

Ultimately, this didn’t work out the way that Cole or those people had thought, which is part of why he came to the realization that he was doing things to impress others rather than being himself. From that point, he made a notable shift in his public persona that still persists. He doesn’t want to be defined by materialistic things or be perceived as vain. He also notes that he had to find God, which indicates that the glorification of wealth within the music industry may have initially deterred his relationship with Him.

Interestingly, less than two weeks before the award show, Cole had discussed his negative perception of materialism on his record, “Chaining Day.” It has also been discussed in several interviews and songs since the June 2013 event.']]), ('Half the time, we be pacifyin’, what they expect from us?
 But that’s treacherous, that shows less of us
 I need y’all to see every part of me
 Every scar and every artery
 Every story that I can recall, then I can fall', [['Cole talks about what he needs to complete before he can officially retire, or “fall.” He is telling his fans that instead of only giving listeners what they are expecting from him, he’s going to be completely transparent and tell as many stories as he can recall.

Since Cole unveiled the album’s title in April of 2018, fans theorized that The Fall Off was titled this way because it would be Cole’s final album and the start of his retirement. However, he had teased possibly retiring nearly two years prior on DJ Khaled’s July 2016 record, “Jermaine’s Interlude,” rapping:

Said all that I could say, now I play with thoughts of retirement

Cole is now contradicting his previous stance as he realizes that there is more that he can divulge to his listeners.

Two days before releasing this song, Cole published an essay titled “The Audacity” in which he discussed several critical periods of his life. He also wrote on the times that he contemplated retirement before ultimately deciding against it. In the essay’s final paragraph, he wrote:

On my career bucket list, there remain a few more items to check off before I give myself permission to enter whatever the next chapter of my life may be.

It is still unknown whether or not The Fall Off will be Cole’s final album, but he seems to be preparing for the final stages of his career.

“Scar” could be connecting this line to the 1994 film, The Lion King, which inspired Cole’s alter ego and is where this song’s title is derived from. The movie’s main antagonist is a lion named Scar, so Cole could be saying that he wants to show his fans his darker side.']]), ('Niggas dissed me, it was nonsense
 I sat ’em down like his father
 My nigga asked, ”Why you bother?
 We should’ve caught him and mobbed him”
 I said, “We gotta move smarter”
 Don’t wan’ be the reason for one more sad song
 I tried to warn niggas they wouldn’t last long
 I hope that you see how they came and they went
 They shots never hit, but they made they attempts', [["J. Cole calls back to his songs that have ridiculed the new wave of rappers, like his December 2016 track, “everybody dies,” and his April 2018 song, “1985.”

“1985” is the most notable; it was made in response to a trend of fans jokingly chanting, “Fuck J. Cole,” that was started by two Miami rappers, Lil Pump and Smokepurpp. The trend became quite popular and was even the title of a now-scrapped song by Pump. Cole eventually caught wind of what he perceived as disrespect, leading him to discuss his opinion on Pump and other artists like him. On one part of the song, Cole raps:

I’m just tellin' you what’s probably gon' happen when you rappin'
‘Bout the type of shit you rappin’ ‘bout
It’s a faster route to the bottom
I wish you good luck
I’m hoping for your sake that you ain’t dumb as you look
But if it’s really true what people sayin’
And you call yourself playin' with my name
Then I really know you fucked, trust
I’ll be around forever ‘cause my skills is tip-top
To any amateur niggas that wanna get rocked
Just remember what I told you when your shit flop
In five years, you gon’ be on Love & Hip-Hop, nigga

Following the song’s release, Cole and Lil Pump had an endearing conversation at Cole’s home in which they discussed the “Fuck J. Cole” situation and more. However, this didn’t stop Pump from falling off as Cole had predicted. Pump’s second album, released in February 2019, was critically panned and sold only 48,000 units in its first week. Pump will likely never regain the amount of attention or success that he had when he rose to stardom in 2017.

One of the other rappers that Cole was speaking to on “1985” is Pump’s friend, Smokepurpp. He has also evidently fallen off; his last release before this song, June 2020’s Florida Jit, sold slightly over 4,700 units in its first week.

Cole is also saying that he had the fatherly sit-down with Pump because he didn’t want to feel guilty if Pump had died a young death due to the topics of his raps."]]), ('I got mud on my shoes, I ain’t gon’ lie', [['While this chorus and song seem to be rapped from the perspective of a young Cole, this bar calls back to a line from January 2019’s “MIDDLE CHILD,” where Cole raps:

The Bentley is dirty, my sneakers is dirty
But that’s how I like it, you all on my dick

Figuratively, the mud on his shoes alludes to having “come from the dirt,” a slang term akin to the ghetto or slums. This ties into the young persona that Cole takes on throughout the song.']]), ('May have a good year like that name on the blimp
 But you know what it takes to be poppin’ this long?
 Dedication on another level niggas never seen in they life
 Celebratin’ all your first downs like they touchdowns bring a price', [['Continuing the above lines about the artists that try to diss him, Cole then alludes to the Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company, particularly the company’s famous blimp.



Rappers like Lil Pump and Smokepurpp, who have dissed Cole, may have one “good year” of success (2017 for them), but their careers will ultimately fail to attain the same longevity that Cole’s career has. He offers the answer as to why: they don’t possess the same dedication and modesty.

Many rappers, with varying career lengths, go broke because of wealth mismanagement, which can often include a lack of saving and a penchant for making unnecessary or reckless purchases. Cole suggests that celebrating after every minor accomplishment can be costly in the long run.']])]

[('They poisoned the well', [['“Poisoning the well” is a logical fallacy in debate culture, where someone inserts a personal attack against the opponent into their argument.

Similarly, black kids face prejudice before being given a chance to reach adulthood.  I promise to slap all that hate out your voice', [['As of this song’s release, Cole is preparing to release The Off-Season, his fourth mixtape, Revenge of the Dreamers III, the third compilation by Dreamville Records, a currently untitled album under his “kiLL edward” alter ego, and The Fall Off, his sixth studio album.

The four projects mentioned above prove that 2019 is a different year for Cole, as he has never released more than one full-length project in a year.

https://twitter.com/JColeNC/status/1088584217951420416']]), ('You good, T-Minus?', [['Ontario, Canadian producer T-Minus co-produced this track with Cole.  Spending they birthdays inside of a cell', [['The estimated number of young adults ages 18-29 in prison increased from 745,200 in 1999, to 813,600 in 2002. It rose to 865,400 in 2006, then began to decline in 2009.

Know I got a angel cause I’m supposed to have a halo

For my ability to make them birds fly']]), ('I got a few mil’ but not all of them rich
 What good is the bread if my niggas is broke?

 That’s my next mission, that’s why I can’t quit', [["Cole mentioned riding first class before on his September 2011 track, “Sideline Story”:

Up in 1st class, laugh even though it’s not funny
See a white man wonder how the fuck I got money
While he sit at coach, hate to see me walk past ‘im
Young black pants sag, headphones blastin’
Know what he askin', “how did he manage?”

His steps towards helping his friends get rich include hiring his college best friend Ibrahim, as manager and current president of Dreamville. Ibrahim’s little brother, Bas, is also a major artist signed to Dreamville."]]), ('The Bentley is dirty, my sneakers is dirty
 But that’s how I like it, you all on my dick', [['On his April 2018 track, “KOD,” Cole raps:

Bentley from his mama’s whip
K-O-D, he hard as shit

Later on the song, he raps:

How ‘bout you just get the fuck off my dick?

To go from his mother’s car to a luxury vehicle illustrates how Cole’s talents earned him success and wealth. However, he does not obsess over material things.

Ibrahim Hamad, Dreamville’s president, tweeted about Cole’s Bentley on the day of the song’s release:

That boy Bentley stay dirty too. No lies on that, I’ll take a picture next time if ya need receipts

This line also comes to life in the music video, as Cole’s Bentley is literally driven through mud.



Cole is a sneakerhead and frequently wears the Air Jordan 1 “Chicago.”']]), ('We coming from a long bloodline of trauma
 We raised by our mamas, Lord, we gotta heal
 We hurting our sisters, the babies as well
 We killing our brothers,', [['Cole is saying we have not yet healed as a people, and as a result we are inflicting pain within our own communities.  Due to multiple circumstances, we see Black on Black violence. Racism has caused an endless cycle of generational trauma that we have not yet begun to heal from.

The Census Bureau reports that over one-third of all Black children in America live with single mothers. Cole himself was raised by a single mother, something he’s touched on numerous times in songs like 2011’s “Breakdown”:

My mother played father cause no other man bothered
Not even my biological, it never seemed logical

On April 2018’s “FRIENDS,” Cole touches on how these traumatic environments can cause long term problems for Black people:

There’s all sorts of trauma from drama that children see
Type of shit that normally would call for therapy
But you know just how it go in our community
Keep that shit inside, it don’t matter how hard it be
Fast forward, them kids is grown and they blowing trees

In turn women of color are more likely than others to suffer both domestic and sexual violence within their communities.']]), ('I just poured somethin’ in my cup
 I’ve been wantin’ somethin’ I can feel
 Promise I am never lettin’ up
 Money in your palm don’t make you real
 Foot is on they neck, I got ’em stuck
 I’ma give ‘em somethin’ they can feel
 If it ain’t ’bout the squad, don’t give a fuck
 Pistol in your hand don’t make you real', [["Cole revisits a prominent theme from his 2018 album KOD. Throughout the project, he attempts to replicate the inner conscious of an addict. For instance, on “The Cut Off” he says:

Gimme drink, gimme dope
Bottom line, I can’t cope

On “Motiv8,” he repeats:

I’m crackin' a smile, I’m dyin' inside
My demons are close, I’m tryin' to hide
I’m poppin' a pill, I’m feelin' alive
I’m feelin' alive, I’m feelin' alive

Cole feels that many of the youth turn to temporary, materialistic things in an effort to feel a sense of fulfillment, which connects to the outro of the song.

Continuing with the message of the track, Cole begins his usual style of a simple storytelling, but then he switches to autotune on the chorus—which is something Cole has rarely or never used in the past. genius_annotations.505:
[('Can you walk with me?
 I hope we’ll find the reason why we often sob, go on, cry
 Painful memories fuck up the vibe
 Though I be tryin’ to let the time heal my mind
 I was once a child, I’ve gotten older
 Still, I know I’m just a boy in God’s eyes
 Fill me up with wisdom and some courage
 Plus endurance to survive, help mine thrive', [['In this outro Cole laments on feelings of despair and the disheartening nature of witnessing repeated tragedies–then offering that hopefully we can find the strength to continue in pursuit of change.  The first four lines asking someone to walk with him could be addressed to several different entities:

A) The female referenced in the first part of the song
B) The human population in general
C) God

A or B) Taken more literally, Cole may be asking the woman referenced in the song, or the human race as a whole to walk with him in pursuit of healing.  That through conversation they may be able to both process some of the deep sadness, and share knowledge so that everyone can become more educated.

C) While the last four lines more exclusively comment on a higher perspective, the entire outro may be a conversation Cole is having with God.  Under this interpretation, Cole begins by asking if God can walk with him and try to explain some reason why these tragedies continue to occur.  Second, Cole comments on the relationship of time and healing: that times supposedly heals all wounds, but while he is now an adult, from God’s perspective he is still very young.  This may imply that he has a lot of healing left to be realized or more literally that from the perspective of an infinite being, Cole is young.  Lastly, Cole asks God to fill him with the wisdom, courage, and endurance to continue on fighting the good fight.']]), ('[Outro]', [['Cole’s singing voice has evolved with each stage of his career. Cole’s singing was notably heard on his December 2014 track, “Apparently.” He would be heard continuing to expand his vocal range on his December 2016 album, 4 Your Eyez Only, on songs like “Ville Mentality” and both parts of “She’s Mine.” Cole again sang on his April 2018 album, KOD, on songs like “Photograph” and “Kevin’s Heart.” On that album, he also began manipulating his voice using the alter-ego kill Edward.

With “Snow on tha Bluff,” Cole continues to expand his vocal range, singing in an unexpected falsetto as he harmonizes with his usual tone.']]), ('Now I ain’t no dummy to think I’m above criticism
 So when I see something that’s valid, I listen
 But shit, it’s something about the queen tone that’s botherin’ me
 She strike me as somebody blessed enough to grow up in conscious environment
 With parents that know ’bout the struggle for liberation and in turn they provide her with
 A perspective and awareness of the system and unfairness that afflicts ’em
 And the clearest understandin’ of what we gotta do to get free', [["Continuing in his discussion of Chicago multi-genre artist Noname, Cole explains that she may have had a “head start” in her social awareness from an upbringing that incorporated education on Black liberation in America into the way she was raised.

However, Noname has discussed her familial upbringing in multiple interviews during her career, and revealed that she grew up with her grandparents on the South Side of Chicago until she was 13 and after moved in with her mother. She delved deeply into her upbringing in a February 2017 interview with the Chicago Tribune:

[My grandmother was] the woman who raised me until I was about 13, 14. My mother owned a bookstore, which she started when she was 24 (in 1991), the same age when she had me, and she ultimately didn’t have time to juggle both the store and raising me — she didn’t know how. She was young and a new entrepreneur, and for her it made sense for me to stay with my grandmother. I saw my mom on weekends. My grandparents had full custody, and my mom was like a visiting relative. Once things slowed down with my mother’s business, I moved back in with her. It was a little strange at first, there was a little resentment, because I took to my grandmother a little more. So when I moved in with my mother, it was a little awkward, but we’re good now.

One interesting part of her youth that Noname frequently addresses is her participation in the Chicago youth media group YOUmedia, where she met and befriended fellow Chicago rappers such as Chance the Rapper, Saba, Cam O'bi, and others. On her participation in the group, Noname said:

[YOUmedia] was my safe place to create and feel understood in a lot of ways, to feel like I could create openly, with vulnerability and not to be judged or criticized… [The transition from poetry to rap] wasn’t hard — the environment was so filled with a variety of art forms. There would be someone singing, rapping, reading a poem, doing a short monologue or dancing — it was like a variety show. Being around a bunch of different people who were rapping, I felt like I could do both. We’d have these cyphers after each open mic.

The stories and perspectives that each of her fellow participants may have rubbed off on her during the youth program may have helped give her confidence in both her musical and social voice, allowing her to be as much of an advocate for change that she is now."]]), ('I struggle with thoughts on the daily

Here, he correlates himself to a slave and even says that he feels as though he has betrayed his black brothers and sisters who are not as fortunate.

On his December 2014 track, “Love Yourz,” Cole discusses how, after receiving wealth and fame, he realized that they were not all that it was made out to be. The entirety of the song discusses this, but here is a portion of the second verse:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5tr_9DozAok"]]), ('Shit, it’s a reason it took like two hundred years for our ancestors just to get freed
 These shackles be lockin’ the mental way more than the physical
 I look at freedom like trees, can’t grow a forest like overnight
 Hit the ghetto and slowly start plantin’ your seeds', [['While the exact timeline of slavery in the Americas is unknown, African slaves are estimated to have been first brought to America by Spanish and Portuguese settlers somewhere from 1501 – 1505. Slavery in America was officially abolished on December 18, 1865 by the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, giving the total duration of slavery in the United States a range of 360 to 364 years.

Cole compares the physical shackles African slaves experience while coming to America to the restrictions that systemic racism in America have on the mindset of Black people in the country. Having been oppressed for the many years and having heard many stories of oppression from past generations, Cole says Black people in America are unable to believe that there is an escape from the subjugation that they experience in society, stressing the importance to free themselves from this restriction before further change can be made.

Cole then gives his own input on how education on racial discrimination and inequality should be undertaken in America, saying that it should be a gradual process and cannot be an undertaking completed overnight. He also says education on the topics in communities should start within the communities themselves, allowing people to gradually rid it from their own community and eventually removing it from the country altogether.

This is a stark contrast from Noname’s strategy on education, as she speaks loudly on the issues on her various social media accounts.']]), ('But damn, why I feel faker than Snow on tha Bluff?
 Well, maybe ‘cause deep down I know I ain’t doin’ enough', [["Snow on tha Bluff is a January 2011 movie about Curtis Snow, an Atlanta robber and crack dealer who, in the film, stole a camera from college kids during a drug deal and made an autobiographical documentary.

The film was so convincing that the Atlanta PD tried to link its footage to a string of home invasion robberies from around the time of the film’s release, but the film was ultimately unconnected from the other events. However, Snow was later arrested in May 2016 on charges for aggravated assault.

Cole plays off the film’s realistic filming style, which seemed like documentary footage to many on the surface but ended up being fictional after deeper investigation. He feels that he may be all talk when it comes to the Black Lives Matter movement, as if he has come up short in his support for the movement.

Notably, Cole comes full circle in the last line of the verse. In the first line of the song, he says that he is perceived as “deep” by the public:

Niggas be thinkin' I’m deep, intelligent, fooled by my college degree

While at first he acknowledges that he is deep on the surface, Cole ends the verse by questioning his inner motives, wondering if he really is interpreting the movement to the fullest extent that he can rather than just acting like he is doing so."]]), ('Niggas be thinkin’ I’m deep, intelligent, fooled by my college degree', [['J. Cole graduated from St. John’s University in Queens, New York in 2007, earning magna cum laude honors and accruing a 3.82 GPA over his tenure. He detailed his college lifestyle in his May 2007 track, “College Boy,” which was released right as he was graduating from school.

Cole is implying that, although he may have earned a college degree, that doesn’t indicate that he can’t continue to be educated by others who are more aware of things that he is not. This ties into the ensuing lyrics in which he broaches a discussion with Noname. He is also saying that his fans falsely place him on a higher pedestal simply because of his education, but he’s warning them not to.

Interestingly enough, Cole majored in communications with a minor in business, two paths of study that may have helped with both the lyrical side of his career, as he communicates through music, and the managerial side, as he is the owner and co-founder of Dreamville Records.']]), ('And the frustration that fills her words seems to come from the fact that most people don’t see

Moreso, Cole is emphasizing that to truly educate the people, it will require more effort than simply posting on social media or “retweeting.” He knows that actually having in-person discussions can have more permanent effects on uneducated people.

On May 29, Noname tweeted:


Poor black folks all over the country are putting their bodies on the line in protest for our collective safety, and y’all favorite top-selling rappers not even willing to put a tweet up. Niggas’ whole discographies be about black plight, and they nowhere to be found.

(Edited for clarity.)


Given the contents of their discographies, many fans perceived Noname’s tweets as allusions to J. Cole and Kendrick Lamar being silent about the current events.

On May 30, Cole was pictured humbly protesting in the streets of his hometown, Fayetteville, NC, a subtle rebuttal to Noname’s shaming.



Despite Cole’s words, Noname has taken an active role in educating people outside of social media. In July 2019, she started Noname’s Book Club, which strives to educate and empower people of color. The club is also active in bringing these books to correctional facilities. Its website reads:

Noname’s Book Club is an online/IRL community dedicated to uplifting POC voices. We do this by highlighting two books each month written by authors of color. In addition to our social media presence, we feel it is highly important to have free in-person meetups to discuss the monthly picks in a safe and supportive environment. Currently, we have six local chapters with plans for continuous growth.

Ultimately, Cole recognizes that he was partially wrong in his commentary on her work, as he wrote this on Twitter the morning after releasing the song:
https://twitter.com/JColeNC/status/1273229943246409728']]), ('My IQ is average, there’s a young lady out there, she way smarter than me

During the protests, she has called out the system of capitalism, the American policing system, and the history of America that white people took over, but has also called out many celebrities, both black and white, for not taking part in the movement and using their platform and resources to progress the cause.

With Noname’s especially harsh critique of wealthy black men playing into white supremacy by not directly calling out the different forms of white supremacy, Cole thought she may have been talking about himself, especially after she made multiple tweets about conscious rappers not speaking up on the issue on May 29, 2020:


Poor black folks all over the country are putting their bodies on the line in protest for our collective safety and y’all favorite top selling rappers not even willing to put a tweet up.

niggas whole discographies be about black plight and they no where to be found


However, Cole has been very involved with the movement, as he marched in his hometown of Fayetteville, North Carolina days after Floyd’s death on top of dropping this song to support the movement.

Follow @noname. I love and honor her as a leader in these times. She has done and is doing the reading and the listening and the learning on the path that she truly believes is the correct one for our people. Meanwhile a nigga like me just be rapping.']])]

“Lean” is a liquid mixture of codeine, promethazine cough syrup and soda. Drinking lean also results in an euphoric experience for the user but has side effects, these include tiredness, lack of energy and drowsiness. These effects, along with the percocet, explain why Juice is feeling “slow.”

On December 8, 2019, Juice WRLD sadly passed away after suffering a seizure from a drug overdose. Juice was found to have had toxic levels of oxycodone and codeine in his system. [('Waste of bread, I need your attention (Skate)', [['“Need” sounds exactly like “knead:” a step in the bread-making process in which the baker mixes the ingredients. Tyler says that he is a waste of bread, “kneading” his lover’s attention. Some nice wordplay.

 (Four, skate, four, skate, four, skate, four, skate)', [['Tyler absolutely loves skating — he’s mentioned it in his music before, and has even done an interview alongside the one and only Tony Hawk, a famous American professional skateboarder.

https://twitter.com/tylerthecreator/status/1139165939658657799']]), ('How can I tell you?

 Ridin’ ‘round town, they gon’ feel this one
 Ridin’ ‘round town, they gon’ feel this one
 Ridin’, ridin’ ‘round town, they gon’ feel this one', [['Upon the release of this album, Tyler tweeted out instructions for the proper way to listen to the album. Among them, he included:

SOME GO ON WALKS, SOME DRIVE, SOME LAY IN BED AND SPONGE IT ALL UP. WHATEVER IT IS YOU CHOOSE , FULLY INDULGE. WITH VOLUME.

To ensure that the full emotional impact of the project is felt, he argued that fans should engage in subconscious activity like driving—or, as this song puts it, “ridin' ‘round town"—where all of their attention can be placed on the album. Tyler tweeted these lines just a few hours after the album’s release:
https://twitter.com/tylerthecreator/status/1129281021713666048?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1129281021713666048&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fgenius.com%2FTyler-the-creator-igors-theme-lyrics']])]
genius_annotations.1241:
[('Please don’t leave me now
 Please don’t leave me now (Don’t leave)
 Please don’t leave me now
 Please don’t leave me now (Don’t leave)
 Please don’t leave me now (Don’t leave)', [['Tyler’s troubled relationship and his fear of split-up between him and his lover are such important themes carrying on throughout IGOR, and they can be explained by comparing the various tracks and their tones.

For example, Tyler uses this phrase for the first time on “EARFQUAKE,” which depicts the potentially stunning emotional and physiological effects of infatuation, by comparing them to the massively destructive force of earthquakes:

Don’t leave, it’s my fault
Don’t leave, it’s my fault
Don’t leave, it’s my fault (Girl)
‘Cause when it all comes crashing down I’ll need you

However, while Tyler expressed that particular feeling by singing passionately, here he uses a disquieting and almost lifeless voice tone, as the darkest side of his love has come over, revealing the primitive jealousy that’s invading him and leading him to anxiety and anger towards his lover and the third person involved.

This dangerous state of mind, still present on the subsequent song “A BOY IS A GUN*,” turns into obsessive devotion on “PUPPET,” causes Tyler/IGOR’s lash-out on “WHAT’S GOOD,” evaporates into the full awareness of the break-up on “GONE, GONE / THANK YOU” and “I DON’T LOVE YOU ANYMORE.”

Nevertheless, Tyler’s initial condition seems to be restored on the final track “ARE WE STILL FRIENDS?”']]), ('Your other one evaporate, we celebrate
 You under oath, now pick a side and if you don’t
 (Run, run, run, run)
 I’ll pick you both
 (Run, run, run, run)', [['Tyler’s feelings of resentment towards his lover and his ex turn into a more dangerous territory – he warns his partner to either commit to the relationship they already have going, or else he just may end up killing both of them out of anger.

The usage of the phrase “Under oath” of course refers to the act of telling the truth in court, a testimony that is told under the complete truth. Tyler wants his lover to choose between him and her, with full on honesty.

This is not the first time Tyler asks his lover for reaffirmation of their love, as on EARFQUAKE he would remark (in a much less aggressive fashion), “I just need some confirmation on how you feel.”']]), ('Don’t call me selfish, I hate sharin’
 This 60-40 isn’t workin’
 I want a hundred of your time, you’re mine', [['Tyler is telling this person that he wants something on the next level; a committed relationship. He’s done with the casual hanging out and wants something real (100%).

60-40 can also be in reference to the 60/40 Relationship Rule which is when each person should put in 60 percent and, in return, expect 40 percent back. Give 60 percent, take 40 percent .

According to  Dr. Amanda Itzkoff, MD most people think a good relationship is a 50/50 proposition.
If, however, both partners instead focus on giving 60% and taking just 40%, the relationship has an overwhelming chance of being successful.']]), ('I wanna be found, passenger in your car (Don’t leave)', [["This could be a reference to his lines from “911 / Mr. Lonely”:

Five car garage
Full tank of the gas
But that don’t mean nothing, nothing
Nothin', nothin', without you shotgun in the passenger

Tyler says he wants to be the passenger in his love interest’s car to convey that he wants to be a part of their life. He wants to be the one who’s in a relationship with this person."]]), ('Janis Joplin spillin’ feelings, now I’m out here moppin’ ’em', [['Janis Joplin was a late 1960s artist that combined folk rock, psychedelia, and blues to create emotionally charged and gut-wrenching songs. The latter genre especially distinguished her considering she was a white suburban female.

In an interview with Stud Terkel, she said:

All you gotta do is have a throat, the throat’s the difference. Everybody’s got feelings inside of them. It’s just the faculty of being able to transform it into music.

Tyler follows in her footsteps by reflecting and expressing his own emotional journey through his music, a process that began with Flower Boy.

Given Tyler’s oblique (and sometimes less so) references to his sexuality, it’s worth mentioning that Joplin famously had sex and long-term romantic relationships with both men and women, and many speculated that she was a lesbian. In response to these claims, she told personal friend and former Grateful Dead manager, Richard Hundgen:

I hear a rumor that somebody in San Francisco is spreading stories that I’m a dyke. You go back there and find out who it is and tell them that Janis says she’s gotten it on with a couple of thousand cats in her life and a few hundred chicks and see what they can do with that!

By comparing himself to her specifically instead of other similar artists associated with emotionally raw lyrics, Tyler makes a deliberate connection.']]), ('I will not fetch the ball', [['This might be another reference to Tyler’s track “911 / Mr. Lonely”, in which he raps:

I never had a dog
So I’ve never been good with bitches
‘Cause I never threw a ball, fetch']]), ('If you can’t understand, I’m a hawk in the gym
 Eyes on the prize, got weight on my chest
 That I need to get off, or I ain’t talkin’ to them', [['Hawks are birds that are known to have very keen eyesight. This characterizes just how focused he is on the prize, which he describes here as getting a weight off his chest (he’s exercising to be strong enough to lift the weight). It’s just another way of saying he’s dedicated to getting rid of this girl.']]), ('Like magic, like magic, like magic, gone
 New magic, new magic, new magic wand
 Like magic, like magic, like magic, gone (Nigga)
 New magic (Woo), new magic, new magic wand', [['Tyler’s envy drives him to believe that by getting rid of his love interest’s ex, his relationship with the love interest will be fixed—as if by ‘magic.’

The ‘magic wand’ Tyler references may be a metaphor for a gun; Tyler elaborates on this metaphor by alluding to killing the ex to win back his love interest in the third verse with the line, “she’s gonna be dead, I just got a magic wand.”

While it’s not clear that the ‘magic wand’ is necessarily a gun, Tyler’s threatening to ‘blow the whole spot up,’ supports this assumption.

Despite many suggestions that the “magic wand” was a reference to the photoshop tool, Tyler confirmed in a tweet that this is not the case.']]), ('It’s not a joke, murder she wrote', [['Murder, She Wrote was a highly-successful crime drama which aired on CBS from 1984 to 1996. Starring Angela Lansbury as a mystery writer who conducts amateur detective work on the side (often unearthing clues that the police do not notice), the series earned Lansbury twelve Emmy nominations and spawned four TV movies.



Tyler is implying that if his love interest chooses to be with this woman, he may have to resort to killing them both.

Tyler may have drawn inspiration here from frequent collaborator Frank Ocean, who references the show on the chorus of his February 2011 track “Lovecrimes:”

Murder, murder, murder she wrote
Love crimes, love crimes']]), ('You roll the dice, hit a seven, sure you right', [["In the game of craps, rolling two dice such that the sum of their values is seven is often the most optimal outcome (though it can sometimes be disadvantageous), and thus the phrase “rolling a seven” (or, alternatively, “hitting a seven”) is associated with good luck. Tyler’s mentor, Pharrell Williams utilizes this phrase in the song “Rollinem 7s” off N.E.R.D’s 2017 album NO_ONE EVER REALLY DIES, in which he raps:

Every time I turn around, I’m rollin' them 7’s"]])]

[('You lost, son, and you’ve been tryna find your way to me
 Ayy, to me, he’s on somethin’ that I hate to see', [['This song presents Tyler at his lowest, both heartbroken and submissively desperate for love. Kanye, being someone who’s had his own fair share of heartbreak, sympathizes with such tragedy. He’s seen similar situations to Tyler’s unfold, notably in 2016’s “Wolves” for example:

You tried to play nice, everybody just took advantage
You left your fridge open, somebody just took a sandwich

It’s worth noting that Tyler cites Kanye as a prominent influence for him in general. Even during his emotional lows, Kanye still maintained a strong confidence, which is what Tyler is searching for at this point.']]), ('[Verse 3: Kanye West]', [['The official lyrics for Kanye’s verse have been heavily debated due to its unmixed, lo-fi sound. On June 19th, 2019, Tyler tweeted an official lyric sheet that didn’t help. In place of Kanye’s verse, he simply wrote:

KANYE LYRICS CANNOT BE TRANSCRIBED



Due to the purposely unverified lyrics, it’s possible that the currently transcribed lyrics aren’t entirely accurate.']]), ('Do you need a hug?', [['https://twitter.com/tylerthecreator/status/1136990220535156744
Tyler jokingly uses misdirection here. The rhyme scheme suggests that he’d rhyme this line with “bread”, which would then be completed with “instead.”

However, he abruptly inserts “a hug” to throw the listener off. This most likely implies that he would’ve asked the person “Do you need head?”

When performing this song live, Tyler sometimes does say “head” instead of hug.']]), ('But at some point, you come to your senses', [['Seemingly this is him being freed from a toxic relationship, but it’s actually Tyler lying to himself, and not being able to let go of this person, he does this a couple of times on the album, even on the final 2 lines of the album;

“A BOY IS A GUN”:

I ain’t gon' repeat myself, but stay the fuck away from me").

The next track on the album (WHAT’S GOOD) ends with “I don’t know what’s harder, letting go or just being okay with it” it shows us that even though he seemingly “came to his senses”, he was just pretending and still can’t let go of this person.

On “GONE, GONE / THANK YOU” Tyler seemingly accepts the loss of this person and he never wants to fall in love again, but that is only because how hurt he is:

And now I’m scarred for life

Once again on the next track I DON’T LOVE YOU ANYMORE Tyler says that he is no longer in love and is completely over it, yet he still chases this love (to an extent) on the last track ARE WE STILL FRIENDS? where he admits that he can’t let go, with even the final 2 lines of the album being:

Can’t say goodbye

Tyler clearly still has deep feelings for this person, even though he pretended like he didn’t because he was left scarred. All of this connects back to the track EXACTLY WHAT YOU RUN FROM YOU END UP CHASING:

Exactly what you run from, you end up chasing. Like, you can’t avoid, but just chasing it and just like trying. Giving it everything that you can.']]), ('[Verse 2: Tyler, The Creator]', [['Tyler’s staccato flow during the second verse is very reminiscent of André 3000’s chorus on Erykah Badu’s “Hello”:

Will this bitch click over for me?
I mean will this woman click over for me?

https://youtu.be/KXGqHYNTNHU?t=77']]), ('I wanna talk, I wanna call you and talk
 I wanna walk to your front door and knock', [["These lines connect to the fact that Tyler is crawling back to his lover and also explores the meaning of the skit “EXACTLY WHAT YOU RUN FROM YOU END UP CHASING”, as he ended up running from his love interest in the previous track “A BOY IS A GUN” when Tyler told his lover:

I'ma leave it at that, I'ma leave us as friends
‘Cause the irony is I don’t wanna see you again
Stay the fuck away from me

 Tyler later comes back chasing after his lover."]]), ('A to Z, nah son, I’m gonna take a breathe', [["This may be a subtle nod to East coast rappers AZ and Nas who’re known for being one of the best unofficial rap duos to come out of the New York hip-hop scene. They’re responsible for songs like 2008’s “Serious” and 1994’s “Life’s A Bitch.”



On the left: Nas; On the right: AZ.


Ye’s usage of the homonym “Nah, son” to “Nas son” may also be in reference to Nas' 2002 sixth studio album God’s Son (as the homonym and album title sound phonetically similar.)"]]), ('Then back to my house and we pack up our bikes
 And we ride through the park, chase the sun', [['Tyler has been very vocal about his love for biking. Not only did he deliver a verse about it on Frank Ocean’s 2017 loosie “Biking,” but he even devoted an entire song, 2013’s “Slater,” to his bike of the same name, explaining in a tweet:

https://twitter.com/tylerthecreator/status/327255730036035584?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw







In an interview with GQ Magazine in August of 2018, Tyler was asked about his ideal day and responded with this:

I would wake up, definitely make breakfast, go on a fucking long-ass bike ride, and it either ends going to a show from a band or going to see a movie. And somewhere swimming in between that.']]), ('I’m your puppet, you control me
 I’m your puppet, I don’t know me
 (Did I wait too long?)
 I’m your puppet
 (Did I wait too long?)
 You control me
 (Did I wait too long?)

[('Update December 21, 2019', [['No cap I thought I was gonna finish this during winter break, but I’m having hella fun irl and everywhere on the internet but Genius so I’m not gonna finish this lol, feel free to peep what I have so far though!']]), ('YUNGBLUD featuring Halsey - “11 Minutes”', [['https://youtu.be/a1RMiMLDsvQ

I’m 11 minutes away and I have missed you all day
I’m 11 minutes away, so why aren’t you here?

I actually have a funny connection to this song, that led it to making my list. “11 Minutes” is on the NBA 2K20 soundtrack, and when the game first dropped (you know I had to cop Day 1), there was a glitch that only one song would be playing in the main menu as you progressed through your MyCareer Prelude. My song happened to be “11 Minutes”, and it was surprisingly fitting, cause there are some intense, heated cutscenes in the storyline, so when they’d lead right into this song on the main menu – where I’m suiting up for the next game and upgrading my attributes – it set the tone for what the energy/mood of the next game would entail. Cause the entirety of the prelude is intense until the very end, so this song was appropriate to be my one looped song.

So basically, NBA 2K20 put me on this song and forced me to listen to it for like 4 hours straight and I have no regrets. Although, I wish that my glitched song was “MONOPOLY” cause that’s on the soundtrack too lol']]), ('Lil Tjay on “War”', [["https://youtu.be/zOB5-Id1ZfU?t=38

Gang with me, anywhere I pop out, I know the thang with me
Every nigga here with me gon' bang with me
Try your luck and bro goin' insane with me
Bodies dropping, that shit ain’t a thing to me

Man, when I first heard the snippet for this song I knew it was bouta be a banger. Like, come on dude. Lil Tjay on a drill beat??? That’s something we could only dream of. But it became a reality, and Tjay definitely did NOT disappoint. The singing rap flow is so hot right now, and Tjay’s ability to incorporate that on such a hard beat is spectacular. Not to mention, Tjay hmm-ing is amazing too.

This verse filled Criterias 1, 3 and 5 for me."]]), ('Kanye West featuring Ant Clemons - OG Water', [['https://youtu.be/-YfG1Xbo4OA

Clean us like the rain in spring
Take the chlorine out our conversation
Let Your light reflect on me
I promise I’m not hiding anything
It’s water

Man, this song had soooooo much potential. This could’ve been my song of the year. I had OG Water on loop alllllll year since Coachella (shoutout Yecord, good times), and this seriously was a phenomenal track in its early stages, ESPECIALLY the Ty Dolla contributions later on. Regardless, I love Ant Clemons so much, and it was after this song that my love for him became bigger than anything I’d ever expected. Ant Clemons really is the goat for OG Water, and I even made the Ant Clemons Discord for him. If you’re tryna join just hit me up. Even though the final product did not live up to expectations, I cannot deny the amount of dopamine that’s been released the past few months because of OG Water. Perhaps it was bias that it was just new Ye, but OG Water allowed Ant Clemons to go on such a long stream of vibe and I appreciated it a lot. Word to Ant Clemons

I love him so much that I drank water live on my Instagram Story, I even wore the Ant Clemons hat for him. I posted it here for you all to watch (NSFW):

https://youtu.be/Ay2pHGpSpVY']]), ('Cochise - Redhead', [["https://youtu.be/ocZ5-53lpvI?t=8

Pull up on the scene
I ain’t gettin' hoes, nigga what the hell that mean?

 Just skip to 1:42 tbh 

I first found Cochise from Dig Me Freestyle earlier this year via a lil uzi fanpage on IG, and man I’m so glad I did lol. Once I heard “Pull up on the scene” when he played a snippet of Redhead on his IG Live, I knew this song was gonna be a banger.

Of course, the baby voice comparisons between him and Carti are gonna arise, but I can say with confidence that Cochise has the superior baby voice, that “Pull up on the scene” is no joke"]]), ('PARTYNEXTDOOR - The News', [['https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nkGixIT4HdM

Never in a million (Lifetimes)
But my love just reached the ceiling
What’s news to you, it ain’t news to me

I FUCKING LOVE PARTYNEXTDOOR. He’s one of those vibes that are too essential to the game that he doesn’t have any bad songs. There’s only a few artists along that line, where literally every single song they drop is gold. When I found out that PARTYNEXTGOAT was gonna drop this year, I threw my basketball at my lamp in excitement and it broke. It’s okay though, cause the goat dropped. PNG’s one of those artists that you can truly resonate with if you’re a hooper. Not everyone’s a hooper or about it, so I can’t be mad when people hate on him. There’s a difference between being uninformed and ignorant, so I can’t be mad at someone who’s asleep

Man’s really bouta drop album of the decade at the beginning of the decade, January 2020 can’t come quick enough']]), ('Dominic Fike - 3 Nights', [["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OWKzRngush4

So I get lost in modern music, watchin' movies

I love the way rap flows are incorporated in this pop song, hopefully he drops more stuff along this vein cause then he’ll become poppin' like that"]]), ('88GLAM featuring NAV - Snow Globe (Remix)', [["https://youtu.be/Mdo6kE47N9Q

Neck look like a snow globe, packin' like a camper (Snow globe)
Treat these bitches stone cold, stunner, I'ma slam her
Molly make her nose cold, got that shit from Canada (Nose cold)

You need to be a certain level of intellectual and have a high enough amount of IQ to truly appreciate the genius of 88GLAM. Yet, at their core, the duo make music for everyone.

88GLAM is such a fucking vibe. Their vibe curation ability is impeccable, they’ve some of the catchiest tracks ever, period. 88G2.5 is so fire man it’s not even funny, Camino and Derek Wise beautifully bounce off each other, and the NAV feature perfectly encapsulates the energy that 88GLAM is moving with. The simplicity in their repetition further reinforces the consistent existence of the vibes that they’re relaying. Ever since then, I’ve been keeping up with the vibes."]]), ('Coi Leray - Good Day', [["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RiKgbBChnhU

Middle finger up to the bullshit

Man what an underrated fun song! No cap shoutout Trippie Redd for putting me on. It has such a chill optimistic turn up vibe, I had this for my alarm clock for a good period of time and I can vouch that I did indeed have plenty of good days.

I also particularly love the harmonies/lower octave paired with the flow at 0:55, easily the best part of the song. And oh yeah, the video’s wavy asf too"]]), ('Kanye West featuring Charlie Wilson - Brothers', [['As soon as I cut the grass low
It’s easier to see the assholes
So I’m sorry for all the miscues
How about I admit that I miss you

 Brothers is hard af to find on the internet so if you want the song message me 

“Brothers” was a clear indicator to me that Kanye can tap into his “old Kanye” bag whenever he needs drop something appropriate. This was also demonstrated when he produced Pusha T’s “Coming Home” in late August, which shows that he still has that skillset.

I wrote a whole thing about the significance of “Brothers” and how it impacted me personally when analyzing the relationship I have with my older brother, but that’s all in Izeezuscord and it’s personal stuff that I just don’t wanna share like that out of the blue. If you’re actually curious about it then join Izeezuscord and you’ll be able to peep

But yeah when this song dropped, my family went to the hospital to visit someone, so I was by myself at home. So like any other regular human being, I blasted music loud as hell in my house, and it appropriately ended up being hella Frank Ocean and this song:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hUZshup3rYk']]), ('’bows', [["‘bows, especially with the apostrophe, suggests 'elbows,’ a shorthand for LB, or “a pound of marijuana.” This serves as a tie-in with Baby still selling reefer in spite of having a couple million, makin' classics, and hanging with four or five killers."]]), ('On stage with the Glizzy', [['Glizzy is a slang for a Glock, a semiautomatic handgun, ubiquitous among gun enthusiasts for its famed reliability, ergonomic superiority, and relative affordability. While Baby continues to keep it real with his people, he is prepared, should he have to cap somebody– even during a stage performance.']]), ('Baby prolly still sell reefer', [['Despite having amassed fame and fortune, Baby nonetheless is suspected to keep it real by remaining close to his humble roots selling cannabis, the lowest-grade of street drug.']]), ('We was in the hood, sellin’ bags, shootin’ choppers
 Fucked around and tried to go and lease a helicopter', [["Whilst in the trap, Lil Baby reflects on “shootin' choppers,” that is, firing AK-47’s or a similar semiautomatic rifle (designed to “chop” down enemies), but he turns this into a pun about presumably being sufficiently fucked up (or audacious) as to try and rent the other kind of chopper, a.k.a. a helicopter."]]), ('Yeah, rest in peace to Bankroll, show ’em how to do it', [['Lil Baby pays tribute to Bankroll Fresh, who was a rapper who blew up after releasing his tracks “Hot Boy” and “Walked In.” Unfortunately, he was tragically gunned down on March 4, 2016.

Coincidentally, both Lil Baby and Bankroll Fresh are from Atlanta, Georgia. This line is also a reference to Bankroll’s September 2014 track “Show Em How To Do It.”']]), ('Private plane, Wi-Fi, on the FaceTime with Johnny
 I told him ice my wrist up, I like to hold my fist up', [['DaBaby shouts-out famous celebrity jeweler Johnny Dang, owner of Johnny Dang & Co. and best known for creating diamond studded grills and customized diamond watches for rappers such as Travis Scott and Kanye West.

DaBaby’s current grill that is featured in his album cover on his debut album Baby on Baby was made by Johnny Dang.



Speaking to DJ Small Eyez he mentioned why he chose Johnny to create his grill saying:

All the rappers go get they shit done you know, people spend a lot of money with him and it gotta be for a good reason.

This isn’t the first time Johnny Dang has been featured in a Quality Control song. In 2017’s “Ice Tray,” Johnny appeared in the music video.']]), ('Wheezy outta here', [['This is the producer tag of Wheezy, who has collaborated with Young Thug and Migos on numerous tracks previously including “Guwop,” “Floyd Mayweather,” “White Sand,” “Chanel (Go Get It)” and many more.']]), ('I’m really a millionaire, still in the projects', [["Lil Baby boasts about his exorbitant wealth, which is evident due to his net worth of approximately $4 million. Despite his newfound wealth, Baby still lives in Atlanta, Georgia and reps his impoverished neighborhood. On his August 2018 track, “Need Mine,” he described his come up in the game and his faithfulness to the streets:

Came up out the trenches a millionaire, a nigga damn near made it
Ran it up and lost it all again, damn near drove me crazy

In a verified annotation on his November 2018 track, “Global,” Lil Baby described his transition to fame and fortune:

The adjustment from coming where I come from to where I’m at now is like I’m still adjusting. I haven’t even made the full adjustment ‘cause it happened so quick. But still, I ain’t get like a deal then I’m like a millionaire. I grinded up on a million dollars. That shit felt great ‘cause I’m like 400, 500, 600, 700, 750, go back down, go back up, then you become a millionaire. You be almost a millionaire before you be a millionaire 'cause you already in the midst of it then once you really become a millionaire, you already be grindin’ so hard you damn near be like, “I deserve it, I deserve it.” The way I got mine. That first million."]])]

Gunna has expressed his love for the bag countless time on tracks such as “Hot”, “Pink Toes” and “Vibes on Vibes” while also naming a song, “Baby Birkin”, after the accessory.



Jordyn Woods with a Birkin bag in Gunna's "Baby Birkin" music video']]), ('Twenty racks don’t feel like nothin’ to me', [['A “rack” is a thousand dollars so “twenty racks” is $20,000. In 2019, it was estimated that NAV’s net worth was $1.5 million, making $20,000 a small amount of money in comparison.']]), ('Trappin’ on the block, I’d never serve a cop', [['“Trap” means to sell drugs so Gunna could be implying here that he doesn’t want to sell drugs to a cop. He could also mean he wouldn’t “serve” or give information to the cops about anything or anyone.

Gunna has his reasons for not liking the police—in June 2018, he and DJ were arrested after drugs were found in his car.']]), ('Came from the streets, it turned me to a beast', [['NAV is likely calling back to his chorus on the late Pop Smoke’s February 2020 track, “Wolves,” where he similarly raps:

Yeah, I was raised in the jungle, it turned me to a beast

NAV was born and raised in a low-income household in Rexdale, a rough neighborhood in Toronto. Rexdale is notorious for having its high rate of gang-violence and thefts. NAV, however, stayed out of trouble as a child and has no known difficulties with the authorities.']]), ('Pullin’ out fifty racks, walkin’ out of Chase', [['JPMorgan Chase Bank, N.A or just Chase Bank is a national bank that’s headquartered in Manhattan, New York. It’s one of the “Big Four” banks in the United States. A “rack” is a thousand dollars so “fifty racks” is $50,000.']]), ('Keep me a razor when I’m in the East
 Open ’em up just like a surgery', [['It’s possible that NAV is talking about how Toronto is located in Eastern Ontario. Rexdale–NAV’s hometown–is a rough neighborhood located in Toronto, full of gang-related crime and thefts.

NAV keeps a knife for protection and compares using it to that of a surgeon, who slices through their patients with a scalpel while performing surgery.']]), ('Cactus Jack me up and down, head to toe', [['Cactus Jack Records is Travis Scott’s record label. In 2019, Cactus Jack collaborated with Michael Jordan to create the Cactus Jack Apparel Collection so Travis could be saying here that he’s dressed in his own Cactus Jack apparel from “head to toe.“



Travis wearing an Air Jordan 1 x Cactus Jack tracksuit']]), ('Fillin’ her nose with some shit I can ski with', [["Cocaine is a stimulant drug that’s snorted through the nose. “Snow“ is common slang for cocaine, as both substances are white and powdery.

This line is reminiscent of NAV’s line on Travis' September 2016 song “beibs in the trap,“ where he rapped:

Got a white bitch snorting up snow"]]), ('(Wheezy outta here)', [['“Wheezy outta here“ is the producer tag for Atlanta producer Wheezy. It’s voiced by Future and was first used on Lil Baby’s and Drake’s May 2018 song, “Yes Indeed.”

Wheezy has produced for all three artists multiple times before—for example, he produced Travis and Gunna’s August 2018 song, “ZOOM“ and NAV’s March 2019 song, “Habits.“']]), ('Hardly get thirsty, got water like a lake', [['“Water“ is slang for pristine and exceptionally clear diamonds. NAV also used the term on his January 2016 hit “Myself“:

Diamonds in my pinky, look like water, make me seasick']])]

genius_annotations.962:
[('Hey look ma, I made it
 Hey look ma, I made it', [['These lyrics make up the title of the track. The repeated six words represent Urie saying he has “made it” in the music industry. Often, new artists will be struggling in the industry, and it is quite tough to “make it” and become a successful musician. Brendon’s parents were likely worried that this would happen to him early on, as it does to most who attempt to make a career for themself out of music. However, he ended up becoming famous and successful, which is what most of the song describes. He is finally able to show his parents and the world that he “made it” despite all of the hardships he may have faced.
One could also take these lyrics sarcastically or ironically. Throughout the track, Urie portrays the message of what happens after fame in a tongue-in-cheek manner. The music video shows a puppet taking the place of Brendon as a clear metaphor of others using him as a puppet rather than a human. Many lyrics give sarcastic praise to the effects of fame, which are not in reality valid. He could be saying, “Hey look ma, I made it” as a way of ironically saying that yes, he may have become successful in the industry, but a lot of things are messed up. The cheery sound of the lyrics and tune could lead one to take it all literally, but along with the music video, which shows the puppet version of Brendon progressively getting more messed up, taking drugs, drinking, getting beaten, arrested, and puking. Throughout these visuals, the happy sounding lyrics create a stark contrast, which could also leave the listener to interpret the lyrics sarcastically.']]), ('So I do the deed, get up and leave
 A climber and a sadist, yeah', [['“Doing the deed” is an idiom for sex. These lines continue the analogy of Urie as a hooker working for the record label.']]), ('Ain’t ready for the latest?', [['This speaks about how the fans weren’t ready for the new album. No one knew anything until a few months before the release. Even the record label that he was with said he should just take the year off. Brendon said that he couldn’t just sit still, and worked on songs in-between shows playing Charlie in the Broadway musical Kinky Boots. He would work on his computer during the show, and produced 2 songs.']]), ('I see it, I want it, I take it, take it', [['This line is similar to one in “Emperor’s New Clothes” from Death of a Bachelor.

I see what’s mine and take it

Both lines evoke the idea of Brendon identifying what he wants out of life and doing what’s necessary to gain it.']]), ('And if you lose, boo-hoo', [['Boo-hoo is a phrase meaning “to cry.” In this context, “boo-hoo” carries a sarcastic connotation, as a way to express a lack of sympathy toward someone, who is behaving overly dramatic, and mock them.

Brendon is ready to take on the next chapter of his life. He is prepared to face challenges and rise above them. If other people have a problem with losing, that’s on them.

In “Emperor’s New Clothes”, Brendon expresses a similar idea in the lyrics

Finders keepers, losers weepers']]), ('This world is full of demons stocks
 And bonds and bible traders', [['Stocks and bonds are two ways to make money in the world of investing. Buying a stock in a company now gives the buyer a share in that company while buying a bond entails long-term debt.

Brendon equates the ills of the financial system with those who use religion for self-profit. They are the prominent examples of “demons” in today’s world. This directly links with the main theme of the album’s title to Pray For The Wicked.

“Bible traders” is reminiscent of the short story “Good Country People” by Flannery O'Connor, in which a bible salesman tricks a young amputee into giving him her prosthetic leg and subsequently leaves her on the roof of a barn. Brendon’s use of a bible trader could point to a record label that seems helpful and wholesome but is ultimately indifferent to the artists they represent.

“Bible traders "could also be wordplay also saying Bible Traitors, meaning people who abandoned their religion for a secular lifestyle, or even the notorious traitor, Judas Iscariot.']]), ('‘Cause I’m a hooker sellin’ songs and
 My pimp’s a record label', [["A pimp is most well known as:

a man who controls prostitutes and arranges clients for them, taking part of their earnings in return.

Pimps are also well known for their almost ownership status of their women, often taking advantage of them for personal gain. In this lyric, Brendon is describing his relationship with the recording industry, often taking advantage of artist’s skills for their own benefit.

In an interview with GQ, Urie discusses balancing the personal and business relationship with his label and the “hooker sellin' songs lyric.

That’s just real. I can write these things because I’m good friends with people at my label. We’ve been able to talk and learn from those experiences. Things like that are tongue in cheek, but I’m not totally bullshitting there. I have felt like that in the past until I took control creatively and business-wise. I can make decisions and not just throw myself into the corner. I’m a hooker selling songs: I’m a glorified shirt salesman. I go on the road and hopefully people buy a shirt and see me play."]]), ('In a golden cathedral
 I’ll be praying for the faithless', [['A Cathedral is the principal church of a diocese with which the bishop is officially associated and that contains the Cathedra or  Bishop’s throne.
Cathedrals serve as the central church for members of different dioceses of the same religion.

Urie was raised on a strictly Mormon house even though he grew up to not believe in god.

Here, a golden cathedral would refer to the highest profile a cathedral could get and even there Urie would still hold his stance on religion for himself and others that think the same.

This line was first alluded to during the album promotion. The Panic! team sent out Mystery Potatoes to fans, and some of the potatoes bore the words

Pray!ng for the fa!thless']]), ('In the garden of evil
 I’m gonna be the greatest', [['“The garden of evil” is a play on the Biblical Garden of Eden. The Garden of Eden is a paradise described in the book of Genesis in which Man co-exists with nature and God looks over both. Here, the biblical original sin takes place and Man is thrown out of paradise as
punishment.

Rather than Urie being the greatest in the Garden of Eden, which would suggest his being holy or pure, he reigns over the garden of evil, indicating Urie’s tongue-in-cheek rejection of religion.



The Garden of Eden']]), ('Some are loyal soldiers while
 These other thorns are rosy', [['Is the cup half empty or half full? Some things are a matter of perspective. Do roses have thorns or do thorns have roses? Roses having thorns would say beautiful things may be potentially dangerous while thorns having roses would say any dangerous thing only pretends to be beautiful.

Again, a difference in the sincerity of Brendon’s friends appears in this verse. Some of his friends are truly genuine in their friendship with him. They are the roses with thorns. Others are two-faced in that they only appear to be genuine. Those are thorns that only appear to be rosy.']])]
genius_annotations.963:
[('Stay up on that rise
 Stay up on that rise and never come down, oh
 Stay up on that rise
 Stay up on that rise and never come down', [['Figuratively, staying on a rise means pushing yourself towards success. If you’re always going up, you’ll never have to fall. Ideally, musical artists would like to be at the peak of their careers all the time.

Of course, the lines can also be taken literally. With a literal understanding, one can’t help but to think of the song’s music video.

In the video, Brendon climbs the side of a skyscraper, also known as a “high-rise” building . Once he reaches the roof, Brendon joins the rest of the band to play the rest of the song. Their playing on top of the skyscraper in the music video could be seen as a symbol of Panic! At The Disco’s recent mainstream success. With that interpretation, one could see the onlookers watching Brendon climb from the ground to the roof as the fans of Panic! At The Disco who have stuck with the band since its early days.']]), ('[Chorus]', [['Brendon revealed at the YouTube Live Release Party for Pray for the Wicked that the chorus for “High Hopes” was the first chorus written for the album.

[The chorus] was given to me by a friend [named] Ilsey. She had this whole idea […] and the perfect message. […] It felt just how I wanted to iterate to people about my childhood, making cardboard cutouts of guitars and acting like a rock star.']]), ('So I got one more run and it’s gonna be a sight to see-eh-eh-eh', [['Some people have interpreted this lyric to mean that Pray for the Wicked will be the last Panic! At The Disco album. Brendon Urie addressed this idea in an interview with NME, expressing his desire to continue Panic! for a long time.

[When writing the lyric] I didn’t take it that way, but who knows. I’m so impulsive. I could say that this will never be the last, but I don’t know what’s going to happen tomorrow. […] I don’t have any plans to stop, ever, anytime soon. I want to be like Mick Jagger’s age and still doing it. That’s the dream!']]), ('It’s uphill for oddities
 The stranger crusaders, ain’t ever wannabes
 The weird and the novelties don’t ever change', [['Panic! at the Disco’s introduction into and approach within the music industry has been far from conventional.

As one of the first bands to garner recognition and success through the internet, they were non-conformists in an industry with deep-rooted conventions and expectations, and instead of having little commercial success, they took the world by storm as “stranger crusaders.”

Throughout commercial radio’s musical eras characterized by the dominance of hip hop and pop, Panic! has always opted for “the weird and the novelties” instead. Notably switching from the pop punk and vaudevillian theatrics of their debut, A Fever You Can’t Sweat Out, to the flower crowns and Beatles-inspired psychedelic and baroque pop of their sophomore album, Pretty. Odd., Panic! takes pride in their label as “oddities.”

By following their own interests and disregarding the pressure of their contemporaries, Panic! established a precedent of never giving up in environments that only seem to ostracize them and of never changing themselves at the expense of their quirks and creativity.']]), ('They say it’s all been done but they haven’t seen the best of me-eh-eh-eh', [['Throughout Brendon Urie and Panic! At The Disco’s career, the band has continually changed genre and shifted the status quo. From the 60’s inspired psychedelia of Pretty. Odd. to the electronic, club synths of Too Weird To Live, Too Rare To Die, Panic! has delved into a new sound with each album.

Though some may believe that Panic! has done everything that is possible for a band to do, Brendon Urie believes that only the best is yet to come for Panic!.

The phrase ‘but they haven’t seen the best of me’ is also reminiscent of a lyric in “This is Gospel,” which states ‘but they haven’t seen the best of us yet.’']]), ('Museum victories, every day', [['“Museum victories” refers to paintings of battles that are often housed in art museums. Rulers or military officers would often commission artwork to commemorate their great victories These works of art are typically over the top in their depictions, portraying the victors as shining heroes.

By striving for “museum victories”, Urie continues the theme of seeking out the very best in everything that he does: achieving goals so great that they deserve to have commemorative paintings commissioned in their honor.



John Singleton Copley, The Death of Major Peirson, 1783']]), ('Manifest destiny, back in the days
 We wanted everything, wanted everything', [['The Manifest Destiny was a belief held by 19th-century American settlers that it was their God-given right – or destiny – to settle westward.

‘Manifest destiny’ in the context of “High Hopes” refers to the view that Brendon was destined to be a musician and share his craft with the world.



American Progress, (1872) by John Gast, is an allegorical representation of the modernization of the new west.']]), ('Didn’t have a dime but I always had a vision', [['In the early days of Panic! At The Disco, the band had very little money– only big passions and dreams in music. Their lack of funds can be especially noted in their first album, and most notably in their single “I Write Sins Not Tragedies.”

In an interview on the Zach Sang Show, Brendon shared:

We had ten thousand dollars to do the first album, we had like no money. […] At that point, we couldn’t even get an extra two hundred dollars to pay someone in to come and play trumpet. We had to pay a sixth grader to come in and play trumpet and we recorded each note separately. So if you listen to “I Write Sins Not Tragedies,” first single off first album, we recorded a girl who was, you know, 13, 14 years old, playing cello one note at a time. And we just took them and sampled them basically, played it like an MPC. So we actually did that like, by hand. It was really crazy.

Despite having little money to keep their band and themselves personally afloat, their vision of achieving success was enough to sustain them.

This line also calls back to a similar lyric in “(Fuck A) Silver Lining”:

Was lost in thought but held the vision

This lyric refers to Brendon possibly being overwhelmed or lost, but ultimately remaining set on his goal.']]), ('Burn your biographies
 Rewrite your history,', [['A biography is a work of writing that outlines a person’s experiences and includes intimate details of their life.

The biography mentioned in the lyrics can easily be equated to Panic!’s discography. Throughout Panic!’s career, they have continually ‘burn[ed]’ and ‘rewrit[ten]’ themselves. Each album has been a completely different genre, from the 60’s style of Pretty. Odd. to electronic club beat of Too Weird To Live, Too Rare To Die. This genre fluidity has caused some fans of their music to come and go; however, Panic! has continually abandoned the status quo and created music that has spoken to them.']]), ('Mama said,', [['When describing the sound of the album, Pray For The Wicked, on Instagram Live Brendon hinted that several songs would give a nod to his mother.

Brendon’s mother has inspired him throughout his life, especially concerning music. In a Mother’s Day Instagram post, Brendon elaborates on his admiration for his mother.

I love you, mom. You’re the reason I am who I am today. My nervous energy on stage is from you. Those high notes I sing are from you. My sick dance moves, I got from you. My overly-animated faces I make when someone says they’re taking a picture, yeah I got that from you. Thank you, mom. You are everything. ❤️ #happymothersday

Though a rumor did circulate that his family kicked him out because he decided to pursue Panic!, Brendon has revealed that they were supportive of his choice.

When I told them I wasn’t going to college or on a Mormon mission, that I don’t believe in God and I was pursuing music, they were like, “You’ve gotta move out.” They cooled off, and when we made our first Panic! at the Disco album, I got a care package from my family with this beautiful letter: “No matter what, we will always love you.”



(L,R) Grace Urie (Mother), Boyd Urie (Father), Brendon Urie, Sarah Urie (Wife)']])]
